1
00:00:06,583 --> 00:00:08,583
[helicopter whirring]

2
00:00:33,583 --> 00:00:35,375
Okay. Here you go.

3
00:00:35,458 --> 00:00:36,625
[indistinct chatter]

4
00:00:36,708 --> 00:00:38,208
[Kujo] Thank you very much.

5
00:00:41,875 --> 00:00:42,875
[sighs]

6
00:00:43,500 --> 00:00:45,458
After a visit to the detention center,

7
00:00:45,541 --> 00:00:48,166
it sure feels good to have
a glass of barley shochu.

8
00:00:48,708 --> 00:00:51,083
You didn't follow my advice,
did you, Mr. Kujo?

9
00:00:52,708 --> 00:00:55,208
You're talking about the Yakuza case?
Thanks for the food.

10
00:00:55,291 --> 00:00:57,041
You went to visit the boss
of the Fushimi-gumi

11
00:00:57,125 --> 00:00:59,083
on Mr. Kyogoku's orders, I'm guessing.

12
00:01:00,500 --> 00:01:01,583
If I don't take the case,

13
00:01:01,666 --> 00:01:04,041
I'm pretty sure
he won't get a fair defense.

14
00:01:04,125 --> 00:01:06,083
How would you define a "fair defense?"

15
00:01:08,625 --> 00:01:11,166
It looks like we'll just
have to agree to disagree.

16
00:01:11,250 --> 00:01:12,625
[melancholy music playing]

17
00:01:12,708 --> 00:01:13,833
I'm saying this, Mr. Kujo,

18
00:01:13,916 --> 00:01:16,000
because I'm worried
about what could happen to you.

19
00:01:17,833 --> 00:01:20,291
You keep this up
and they won't just disbar you.

20
00:01:22,208 --> 00:01:23,916
Sure, they could throw me in jail.

21
00:01:24,708 --> 00:01:27,125
Those guys'll do whatever it takes
to protect themselves.

22
00:01:29,083 --> 00:01:31,541
In other words,
you're worried about my actual survival.

23
00:01:31,625 --> 00:01:33,500
You could lose what's most dear to you.

24
00:01:36,291 --> 00:01:37,708
Even now, it's not too late.

25
00:01:37,791 --> 00:01:39,541
I'll say it as often as I have to.

26
00:01:41,458 --> 00:01:43,458
I'm really worried about you, Mr. Kujo.

27
00:01:47,166 --> 00:01:49,875
Mr. Horikawa was sentenced to death today.

28
00:01:50,541 --> 00:01:54,125
Mr. Horikawa?
You mean the case you were removed from?

29
00:01:54,875 --> 00:01:55,708
Yeah.

30
00:01:57,333 --> 00:01:59,791
It still bothers me.
I wanted to see it through to the end.

31
00:02:02,375 --> 00:02:04,541
I wasn't responsible for the result.

32
00:02:05,541 --> 00:02:07,791
But all the same, it isn't easy to accept.

33
00:02:22,791 --> 00:02:24,625
Excuse me. Another round, please.

34
00:02:24,708 --> 00:02:25,666
[waiter] Coming up.

35
00:02:25,750 --> 00:02:27,208
[music fades]

36
00:02:27,291 --> 00:02:28,333
Thank you very much.

37
00:02:28,875 --> 00:02:29,958
[waiter] Sure thing.

38
00:02:30,041 --> 00:02:33,500
[Yakushimae] I'm really enjoying
this column of yours, Ms. Ichida.

39
00:02:33,583 --> 00:02:34,583
I'm glad to hear that.

40
00:02:34,666 --> 00:02:36,166
[chuckles]

41
00:02:36,250 --> 00:02:39,291
Oh, speaking of.
About that favor I asked you for…

42
00:02:39,375 --> 00:02:42,958
Setting up interviews with people who
are trying to reintegrate into society?

43
00:02:43,041 --> 00:02:43,875
Yes.

44
00:02:44,500 --> 00:02:48,125
That's my specialty.
I'd be delighted to give you a hand.

45
00:02:48,208 --> 00:02:49,625
[Ichida] Thank you very much.

46
00:02:49,708 --> 00:02:50,708
Not at all.

47
00:02:51,416 --> 00:02:53,625
Um, I hope you don't mind my asking,

48
00:02:53,708 --> 00:02:57,083
but how'd you get into
writing something like this?

49
00:02:57,166 --> 00:02:58,041
Oh.

50
00:02:59,083 --> 00:03:02,375
I started out reporting for
a weekly magazine. You know the kind.

51
00:03:02,458 --> 00:03:05,166
I had just landed a job
at a big publishing company,

52
00:03:05,250 --> 00:03:08,166
and as a new hire,
I was assigned to this gossip rag.

53
00:03:08,250 --> 00:03:12,041
Around that time, a random act of violence
was in the news, a murder.

54
00:03:12,125 --> 00:03:14,041
A random act of violence?

55
00:03:14,125 --> 00:03:17,875
It was on a bullet train.
Around 20 years ago.

56
00:03:17,958 --> 00:03:20,125
There was a middle-aged executive
who was killed

57
00:03:20,208 --> 00:03:24,125
while trying to defend another passenger
from some deranged guy with an axe.

58
00:03:24,625 --> 00:03:26,208
Oh, right. That one.

59
00:03:26,291 --> 00:03:28,291
[Ichida] At first,
we ran the story of a hero.

60
00:03:28,375 --> 00:03:29,833
An elite businessman and graduate

61
00:03:29,916 --> 00:03:33,791
<i>from the University of Tokyo's</i>
<i>Faculty of Law who saved a life.</i>

62
00:03:33,875 --> 00:03:35,583
<i>But right after</i>
<i>that article went to press,</i>

63
00:03:35,666 --> 00:03:37,666
I got a call from my editor-in-chief.

64
00:03:38,666 --> 00:03:40,541
Dig around in the big hero's private life

65
00:03:40,625 --> 00:03:44,208
and find some gossip about women,
anything with sex.

66
00:03:44,291 --> 00:03:46,250
[tense music playing]

67
00:03:46,333 --> 00:03:48,333
[Ichida] <i>A week later, we ran an article</i>

68
00:03:48,416 --> 00:03:51,375
<i>about how the elite businessman</i>
<i>was involved in sugar dating.</i>

69
00:03:52,166 --> 00:03:54,458
<i>The magazine sold like crazy.</i>

70
00:03:54,541 --> 00:03:57,166
<i>And suddenly,</i>
<i>public opinion turned against him.</i>

71
00:03:57,250 --> 00:03:59,291
The hero who saved a stranger's life

72
00:03:59,375 --> 00:04:02,750
was transformed into an object
of endless scrutiny and mockery.

73
00:04:06,625 --> 00:04:09,500
Right after that,
I quit working for the weekly magazine,

74
00:04:09,583 --> 00:04:11,125
and then I left the company.

75
00:04:12,458 --> 00:04:16,041
I still regret writing that article,
hurting a family like that.

76
00:04:16,916 --> 00:04:19,833
I'm sorry for making you think
about such a painful memory.

77
00:04:20,833 --> 00:04:23,583
It's not your fault.
I think about it all the time.

78
00:04:26,333 --> 00:04:30,000
After the first article was published,
an acquaintance at the funeral home

79
00:04:30,083 --> 00:04:33,958
let me pose as an employee so I could
get information on the victim's family.

80
00:04:35,791 --> 00:04:37,333
<i>It was a very small affair,</i>

81
00:04:37,416 --> 00:04:40,375
<i>a quiet family funeral</i>
<i>with just the mother and son.</i>

82
00:04:40,458 --> 00:04:43,083
[weeping]

83
00:04:43,166 --> 00:04:47,000
[Ichida] <i>The son was comforting his mother</i>
<i>as she knelt by the body, weeping.</i>

84
00:04:47,958 --> 00:04:50,833
I just couldn't bring myself
to talk to them.

85
00:04:52,416 --> 00:04:57,083
The son stayed up all night
just watching the incense burn.

86
00:04:59,458 --> 00:05:01,833
<i>I'm sure he wanted to cry and scream.</i>

87
00:05:02,333 --> 00:05:03,750
<i>But it looked to me like</i>

88
00:05:03,833 --> 00:05:07,375
<i>he was desperately trying to bottle up</i>
<i>all his feelings.</i>

89
00:05:13,041 --> 00:05:17,041
Well, we ended up drinking
on the roof again after all, huh?

90
00:05:18,416 --> 00:05:20,583
Black Thunder would be lonely otherwise.

91
00:05:22,750 --> 00:05:24,416
This is the last one, girl.

92
00:05:25,791 --> 00:05:27,958
I think this might be it for me, Mr. Kujo.

93
00:05:29,250 --> 00:05:30,166
I understand.

94
00:05:31,250 --> 00:05:33,500
[Karasuma] Mr. Kujo doesn't get it,
does he?

95
00:05:33,916 --> 00:05:34,750
RINO

96
00:05:34,833 --> 00:05:36,833
[music fades]

97
00:05:39,750 --> 00:05:41,541
Just answer the call.

98
00:05:41,625 --> 00:05:43,291
Don't keep your daughter waiting.

99
00:05:46,458 --> 00:05:48,666
I can tell it's her
by the look on your face.

100
00:05:55,250 --> 00:05:56,250
Hi, sweetie.

101
00:05:58,291 --> 00:05:59,250
Mmm.

102
00:06:01,750 --> 00:06:02,750
Mm-hmm.

103
00:06:04,250 --> 00:06:05,083
Of course, I will.

104
00:06:06,666 --> 00:06:08,666
Fifteenth of August. I won't forget.

105
00:06:10,708 --> 00:06:11,750
Mmm.

106
00:06:14,291 --> 00:06:15,333
I promise you.

107
00:06:17,500 --> 00:06:18,416
Yeah.

108
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:20,000
Bye-bye.

109
00:06:25,333 --> 00:06:26,916
Did you just make a promise?

110
00:06:27,625 --> 00:06:28,500
Yeah.

111
00:06:29,875 --> 00:06:31,958
She put me in a tricky position.

112
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:34,375
Daddy, you're always so busy,

113
00:06:34,458 --> 00:06:37,500
so I'm making a reservation with you
for my birthday a month early.

114
00:06:37,583 --> 00:06:39,208
[Karasuma chuckles]

115
00:06:41,833 --> 00:06:44,833
Well, you absolutely have to keep
a promise to your daughter.

116
00:06:45,333 --> 00:06:46,166
Right.

117
00:06:51,666 --> 00:06:54,958
Mr. Kujo, what does family mean to you?

118
00:06:58,583 --> 00:07:01,291
I guess it's something
you can't escape from.

119
00:07:01,375 --> 00:07:02,583
Can't escape from?

120
00:07:02,666 --> 00:07:04,666
[melancholy music playing]

121
00:07:05,625 --> 00:07:07,791
It doesn't matter how far you run

122
00:07:08,583 --> 00:07:10,333
or if you change your last name.

123
00:07:11,541 --> 00:07:14,833
It latches onto your back
and won't let go.

124
00:07:14,916 --> 00:07:18,250
If you try to force it off,
you'll pull off your own flesh too.

125
00:07:18,875 --> 00:07:20,833
You're talking about the Kurama family?

126
00:07:23,916 --> 00:07:25,875
How come you hate them so much?

127
00:07:25,958 --> 00:07:28,166
[upbeat music playing]

128
00:07:28,250 --> 00:07:30,916
If I think way back,
it might be because of my name.

129
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:31,833
Your name?

130
00:07:32,708 --> 00:07:35,750
When you take the written character
for "human" and spell it backwards,

131
00:07:35,833 --> 00:07:37,166
you get "Taiza," funny enough.

132
00:07:38,875 --> 00:07:40,916
Apparently, the name was my father's idea.

133
00:07:42,833 --> 00:07:44,583
So of course, when I was growing up,

134
00:07:44,666 --> 00:07:47,708
the other kids would tease me
and call me "backwards human."

135
00:07:49,750 --> 00:07:52,666
I told myself, "What an awful name
he decided to give me."

136
00:07:53,583 --> 00:07:55,708
I've never stopped resenting him for that.

137
00:07:56,458 --> 00:07:58,458
I went through something like that too.

138
00:07:58,541 --> 00:08:01,625
My last name has the word "crow" in it,
so they said it was bad luck.

139
00:08:01,708 --> 00:08:03,250
All the kids teased me about it.

140
00:08:05,291 --> 00:08:07,041
I wonder which of the two is worse.

141
00:08:08,291 --> 00:08:12,041
A backwards human… or a crow.

142
00:08:12,125 --> 00:08:14,166
[chuckles]

143
00:08:14,250 --> 00:08:17,333
Yeah, I wonder which is worse. [chuckles]

144
00:08:21,625 --> 00:08:22,666
[sighs]

145
00:08:25,083 --> 00:08:27,375
But your daughter isn't a Kurama,
and you know it.

146
00:08:28,833 --> 00:08:30,625
So you should keep your promise
and go see her.

147
00:08:33,500 --> 00:08:34,666
Absolutely.

148
00:09:22,458 --> 00:09:29,458
I’M NOT HERE

149
00:09:30,083 --> 00:09:32,083
[snoring]

150
00:09:32,166 --> 00:09:33,458
[music fades]

151
00:09:36,500 --> 00:09:38,500
[theme music playing]

152
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:15,125
[groans]

153
00:10:16,791 --> 00:10:18,125
[groans]

154
00:10:18,208 --> 00:10:19,625
My back hurts.

155
00:10:20,208 --> 00:10:21,583
This place is a total dump.

156
00:10:21,666 --> 00:10:22,750
[man 2 groans loudly]

157
00:10:24,541 --> 00:10:25,541
[man 2 laughs]

158
00:10:25,625 --> 00:10:26,958
[man 2] Hey, hey. Hey.

159
00:10:27,041 --> 00:10:29,125
Wow, great place you got here. [laughs]

160
00:10:30,083 --> 00:10:33,041
Excuse us. Here's the key. [chuckles]

161
00:10:35,875 --> 00:10:39,166
Oh, hey, everything's cool.
I stuck to the back roads all the way.

162
00:10:39,791 --> 00:10:41,125
A pleasure doing business.

163
00:10:41,208 --> 00:10:42,083
Let's go.

164
00:10:42,166 --> 00:10:43,291
[tense stinger]

165
00:10:47,916 --> 00:10:50,333
[man 1] Hey, how are we getting back?

166
00:10:50,416 --> 00:10:53,708
Uh… We'll take the bullet train
from Oyama Station.

167
00:10:54,375 --> 00:10:56,083
How are we getting to the station?

168
00:10:56,166 --> 00:10:59,083
[chuckles] Thirty-nine minutes by foot,
it says.

169
00:10:59,166 --> 00:11:00,375
What the hell?

170
00:11:02,541 --> 00:11:04,708
Bad enough they've got us
delivering boosted cars,

171
00:11:04,791 --> 00:11:07,791
which is crazy risky for a crappy 30,000.

172
00:11:07,875 --> 00:11:09,333
Such bullshit!

173
00:11:09,416 --> 00:11:11,666
We're gofers, dude. What do you expect?

174
00:11:12,875 --> 00:11:14,083
Gofers, huh?

175
00:11:16,166 --> 00:11:19,041
Sugawara's looking down on us,
that bastard!

176
00:11:20,125 --> 00:11:21,000
[man 2] What?

177
00:11:21,708 --> 00:11:23,583
Yo, you dissing Mr. Sugawara?

178
00:11:25,125 --> 00:11:26,000
Hey.

179
00:11:26,750 --> 00:11:28,250
Let's go rip off that car dealer.

180
00:11:28,333 --> 00:11:29,166
Huh?

181
00:11:29,708 --> 00:11:31,750
Bro, I scoped out the safe
and the security camera.

182
00:11:31,833 --> 00:11:33,291
Are you crazy? That's a bad idea.

183
00:11:33,375 --> 00:11:35,500
We don't know what kind of scary guys
he's connected to.

184
00:11:35,583 --> 00:11:36,875
- Hey.
- [grunts]

185
00:11:37,958 --> 00:11:39,958
Better not get caught then, right?

186
00:11:40,041 --> 00:11:41,625
[tense music playing]

187
00:11:41,708 --> 00:11:43,708
[metal rattling]

188
00:11:53,750 --> 00:11:55,833
[thugs shouting]

189
00:11:56,375 --> 00:11:58,750
- [man 1] Hey! What are you doing, huh?!
- [thug] Get over here!

190
00:11:58,833 --> 00:12:00,791
- Get down, now!
- [thug 2] Grab him! Now!

191
00:12:00,875 --> 00:12:03,000
Where's the money? Where's the safe? Huh?!

192
00:12:03,083 --> 00:12:05,208
- [thug 1] Get him!
- [thug 2] What are you gonna do now?

193
00:12:05,291 --> 00:12:07,166
[thug 1] Open the safe!

194
00:12:07,250 --> 00:12:10,041
Open the safe!

195
00:12:11,041 --> 00:12:12,958
[thugs laugh]

196
00:12:13,041 --> 00:12:14,708
- [thug 1] Yeah!
- [thug 2] Piece of cake.

197
00:12:14,791 --> 00:12:16,833
That car dealer was shitting his pants.

198
00:12:16,916 --> 00:12:18,500
I almost shit mine when Inukai called me.

199
00:12:18,583 --> 00:12:21,125
He goes, "Hurry up, dude,
bring anything that looks like a weapon."

200
00:12:21,208 --> 00:12:25,250
Okay, dump those tools tomorrow.
It's garbage pickup day.

201
00:12:25,333 --> 00:12:26,458
Not here though.

202
00:12:27,583 --> 00:12:28,708
Got it.

203
00:12:29,708 --> 00:12:33,625
[thug 1] So, we gonna go to a strip club
and party with this cash?

204
00:12:33,708 --> 00:12:34,708
[laughs]

205
00:12:36,041 --> 00:12:37,875
Let's play a game before we go.

206
00:12:38,583 --> 00:12:39,625
A game?

207
00:12:43,291 --> 00:12:45,125
A trust game.

208
00:12:54,708 --> 00:12:56,333
We do this to each other.

209
00:12:57,500 --> 00:12:59,416
It doesn't work without trust, right?

210
00:13:01,666 --> 00:13:03,333
You do it to me first.

211
00:13:04,375 --> 00:13:06,458
[chuckles] I'm a bit clumsy, so…

212
00:13:08,666 --> 00:13:09,583
I'll show you.

213
00:13:13,541 --> 00:13:15,541
[breathes shakily]

214
00:13:23,833 --> 00:13:24,708
[grunts]

215
00:13:26,333 --> 00:13:29,958
[screams]

216
00:13:30,041 --> 00:13:32,041
[whimpering]

217
00:13:37,958 --> 00:13:40,250
- Does it hurt, Komatsu?
- [Komatsu moaning]

218
00:13:40,333 --> 00:13:42,166
This is where the trust game begins.

219
00:13:43,291 --> 00:13:46,166
That cop Arashiyama's daughter,
the one who got dropped,

220
00:13:46,250 --> 00:13:48,708
nobody would've found out
if you hadn't snitched!

221
00:13:48,791 --> 00:13:50,083
[whimpering]

222
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:53,416
What's your story for this
at the hospital?

223
00:13:53,500 --> 00:13:55,500
[Komatsu wailing]

224
00:13:58,750 --> 00:14:00,666
What's your story for this?

225
00:14:03,416 --> 00:14:06,250
I went too far. I was pretending
to cut off my own fingers.

226
00:14:09,500 --> 00:14:10,791
- Good.
- [music ends]

227
00:14:10,875 --> 00:14:12,375
- [cries out]
- [laughs]

228
00:14:16,250 --> 00:14:18,833
[Mrs. Karasuma] What's gotten into you
all of a sudden?

229
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:23,291
I wanted the house to be like when
I was a kid with flowers everywhere.

230
00:14:25,041 --> 00:14:26,166
[Mrs. Karasuma] I see.

231
00:14:30,958 --> 00:14:32,041
Is something up?

232
00:14:32,875 --> 00:14:33,750
Huh?

233
00:14:35,208 --> 00:14:36,458
You look a little sad.

234
00:14:39,500 --> 00:14:42,208
My job with Mr. Kujo.
I've decided to quit.

235
00:14:43,375 --> 00:14:44,333
Why is that?

236
00:14:44,833 --> 00:14:47,666
I got a lot out of it.
Why not try somewhere else?

237
00:14:48,583 --> 00:14:51,125
Have you decided who you want to work for?

238
00:14:51,208 --> 00:14:52,125
Mm-hmm.

239
00:14:55,500 --> 00:14:58,791
What sort of person is this new attorney?
Is he a good person?

240
00:15:00,208 --> 00:15:05,250
I'd say it depends on your standards.
What do you consider good or bad?

241
00:15:08,625 --> 00:15:10,666
Whether they can help people or not.

242
00:15:15,041 --> 00:15:18,125
Your dad was made out to be
a bad person after he died.

243
00:15:20,458 --> 00:15:22,291
He was killed by a criminal.

244
00:15:23,666 --> 00:15:25,958
And then he was killed again
by the public.

245
00:15:27,958 --> 00:15:29,083
At the time…

246
00:15:31,250 --> 00:15:33,916
nobody lifted a finger
to help us deal with it all.

247
00:15:37,291 --> 00:15:38,916
So I want you to be…

248
00:15:42,500 --> 00:15:43,833
one of the good guys,

249
00:15:45,208 --> 00:15:47,875
an attorney who helps those
who are suffering and in need.

250
00:15:51,125 --> 00:15:52,291
I will, Mom.

251
00:15:52,375 --> 00:15:54,375
[tender music playing]

252
00:15:59,500 --> 00:16:01,625
You know, I'm feeling okay now.

253
00:16:02,583 --> 00:16:03,458
[Karasuma] Mmm.

254
00:16:06,500 --> 00:16:07,458
Although…

255
00:16:09,583 --> 00:16:11,375
I wanna ask you for something.

256
00:16:11,875 --> 00:16:12,833
What is it?

257
00:16:14,958 --> 00:16:16,291
When can I see Mr. Kujo?

258
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:22,250
NAGARAGI LAW OFFICE

259
00:16:22,333 --> 00:16:25,041
Mr. Nagaragi,
it's an honor to be working with you.

260
00:16:25,125 --> 00:16:26,416
The honor is mine.

261
00:16:28,625 --> 00:16:30,625
- [Karasuma] It's a pleasure.
- Likewise.

262
00:16:30,708 --> 00:16:34,666
We're delighted to have you on board,
Mr. Karasuma, but I'm a little worried.

263
00:16:34,750 --> 00:16:35,791
About what?

264
00:16:36,583 --> 00:16:38,875
I'm worried that my old friend Mr. Kujo

265
00:16:39,708 --> 00:16:41,000
<i>is alone again.</i>

266
00:16:52,291 --> 00:16:54,083
[music fades]

267
00:17:01,750 --> 00:17:03,625
[metal clattering]

268
00:17:09,375 --> 00:17:11,083
[Mibu] Long time no see, Inukai.

269
00:17:12,166 --> 00:17:13,291
What do you want?

270
00:17:13,791 --> 00:17:15,750
So that's the reception
you give to someone

271
00:17:15,833 --> 00:17:17,916
who did ten years because of your orders?

272
00:17:19,208 --> 00:17:21,500
A trip down memory lane,
that's what you want?

273
00:17:26,166 --> 00:17:29,125
- How many times did you visit me?
- You refused to see me.

274
00:17:29,666 --> 00:17:32,875
So show me that you're serious
and visit me more than once!

275
00:17:35,833 --> 00:17:36,958
But I'm so over that.

276
00:17:37,958 --> 00:17:41,083
Three million isn't enough
for doing Arashiyama's daughter.

277
00:17:41,666 --> 00:17:42,708
I want three hundred.

278
00:17:42,791 --> 00:17:44,416
[tense music playing]

279
00:17:44,500 --> 00:17:46,541
- Three hundred million?
- [Inukai] Yeah.

280
00:17:47,125 --> 00:17:49,000
I turned up some interesting information.

281
00:17:49,666 --> 00:17:53,125
<i>You had orders</i>
<i>to get rid of Arashiyama's daughter.</i>

282
00:17:53,208 --> 00:17:56,041
<i>She was sleeping with Koyama,</i>
<i>the head of a porn studio.</i>

283
00:17:56,125 --> 00:17:59,375
<i>Those orders came from Kyogoku</i>
<i>of the Fushimi-gumi.</i>

284
00:17:59,958 --> 00:18:02,291
So then you used us.
Kids who didn't have a clue.

285
00:18:02,375 --> 00:18:04,041
Three hundred million is still cheap!

286
00:18:04,125 --> 00:18:05,125
What is all this?

287
00:18:07,625 --> 00:18:09,000
It's ancient history.

288
00:18:10,916 --> 00:18:12,875
[Inukai] It's not ancient history!

289
00:18:12,958 --> 00:18:14,875
[door slides open]

290
00:18:29,625 --> 00:18:32,375
[Inukai] You know who this belongs to,
right?

291
00:18:33,458 --> 00:18:36,166
<i>We've got your right-hand man, Kuga.</i>

292
00:18:38,125 --> 00:18:40,541
Mr. Sugawara wants to talk to you.

293
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:45,625
You had Kuga work
at Mr. Sugawara's nursing home.

294
00:18:46,125 --> 00:18:49,208
You sniffed out some dirt,
leaked it to the media, and ruined him.

295
00:18:49,291 --> 00:18:50,916
You won't get away with this.

296
00:18:58,166 --> 00:18:59,791
Three hundred million yen.

297
00:19:00,291 --> 00:19:01,625
You'll deliver it in a week.

298
00:19:02,500 --> 00:19:03,500
[sniffs]

299
00:19:03,583 --> 00:19:05,125
You're the ancient history,

300
00:19:05,833 --> 00:19:07,083
Mr. Mibu.

301
00:19:31,833 --> 00:19:33,500
[music fades]

302
00:19:40,750 --> 00:19:44,750
I heard the kid who killed President
Koyama's mistress is blackmailing you.

303
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:50,041
I always have my ear to the ground.

304
00:19:51,250 --> 00:19:55,708
The kid and Sugawara are trying to
shake you down for 300 million yen, right?

305
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:00,166
As soon as you pay them even once,
you're doomed.

306
00:20:01,833 --> 00:20:05,625
They'll come back again and again
until they've picked you clean.

307
00:20:07,458 --> 00:20:08,708
Listen, Mibu.

308
00:20:09,250 --> 00:20:12,125
I'll step in for you
and make this all go away.

309
00:20:16,083 --> 00:20:17,125
No, thanks.

310
00:20:18,708 --> 00:20:21,083
It's my mess. I can deal with it myself.

311
00:20:25,125 --> 00:20:26,208
[chuckles]

312
00:20:26,958 --> 00:20:28,166
That so?

313
00:20:28,250 --> 00:20:29,250
Well, watch yourself.

314
00:20:29,833 --> 00:20:31,041
Thank you very much.

315
00:20:31,541 --> 00:20:32,583
Excuse me.

316
00:20:38,375 --> 00:20:40,375
You're the one who should watch yourself.

317
00:20:42,916 --> 00:20:44,916
- [rhythmic banging]
- [breathing heavily]

318
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:56,166
[door opens]

319
00:20:58,333 --> 00:20:59,500
Mibu's here!

320
00:21:08,083 --> 00:21:10,833
Mibu! Show us the 300 million yen.

321
00:21:11,583 --> 00:21:13,750
Kuga, are you alive?

322
00:21:13,833 --> 00:21:16,208
No. I'm dead.

323
00:21:16,291 --> 00:21:17,208
[chuckles]

324
00:21:17,291 --> 00:21:18,250
Good.

325
00:21:18,333 --> 00:21:19,916
[chuckles] I'll get you out of here.

326
00:21:20,500 --> 00:21:21,333
Okay.

327
00:21:21,416 --> 00:21:23,875
Do you think now's the time
to be making jokes?!

328
00:21:24,375 --> 00:21:27,708
Hey, you came empty-handed.
Cough up the cash.

329
00:21:27,791 --> 00:21:29,458
Your yapping is so loud.

330
00:21:31,291 --> 00:21:32,291
I'm not gonna pay, idiot.

331
00:21:32,375 --> 00:21:33,666
[ominous music playing]

332
00:21:33,750 --> 00:21:36,041
[Sugawara] Are you messing with me, Mibu?

333
00:21:39,791 --> 00:21:40,708
[chuckles]

334
00:21:40,791 --> 00:21:44,583
You used Kuga to ruin
my nursing home business, didn't you?

335
00:21:45,375 --> 00:21:47,708
I don't want just 300 million yen.

336
00:21:47,791 --> 00:21:50,083
Give me all of it,
everything you're worth.

337
00:21:51,125 --> 00:21:52,625
If you don't hand it over,

338
00:21:52,708 --> 00:21:55,083
I'll bury the two of you
deep in the mountains.

339
00:21:55,166 --> 00:21:56,958
I won't pay you a damn thing.

340
00:21:57,041 --> 00:21:58,875
[grunts]

341
00:22:00,875 --> 00:22:02,333
In fact, you owe me for the watch.

342
00:22:03,750 --> 00:22:06,375
Are you gonna go running
to Mr. Kyogoku for help?

343
00:22:06,458 --> 00:22:08,250
There's nobody here to rescue you.

344
00:22:09,166 --> 00:22:10,083
Moron!

345
00:22:11,750 --> 00:22:13,750
I always come ready for anything,

346
00:22:14,666 --> 00:22:16,208
Mr. Sugawara.

347
00:22:17,166 --> 00:22:18,000
Huh?

348
00:22:18,083 --> 00:22:20,375
- [grunts]
- [yells]

349
00:22:20,458 --> 00:22:21,833
What the hell?!

350
00:22:22,750 --> 00:22:25,125
[fighting and shouting]

351
00:22:25,875 --> 00:22:26,750
[man 1] Shut up!

352
00:22:26,833 --> 00:22:28,833
[fighting and shouting continues]

353
00:22:39,458 --> 00:22:41,125
Are you okay, Kuga?

354
00:22:42,416 --> 00:22:43,416
[winces]

355
00:22:43,500 --> 00:22:46,041
Does it seem like I'm okay?

356
00:22:46,125 --> 00:22:47,375
You're a masochist. You'll live.

357
00:22:47,458 --> 00:22:48,750
I'm not a masochist.

358
00:22:51,875 --> 00:22:52,708
Hey.

359
00:22:52,791 --> 00:22:54,458
[men panting, groaning]

360
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:57,375
[Inukai] Let go of me, damn it! [yells]

361
00:22:58,083 --> 00:22:59,125
[Sugawara panting]

362
00:23:01,708 --> 00:23:03,708
[breathing heavily]

363
00:23:07,958 --> 00:23:09,208
[groans]

364
00:23:09,291 --> 00:23:11,458
If you're gonna kill me, get on with it,

365
00:23:12,375 --> 00:23:13,375
Mibu.

366
00:23:15,041 --> 00:23:16,666
Careful what you wish for.

367
00:23:19,791 --> 00:23:21,250
I'm not gonna kill you.

368
00:23:25,291 --> 00:23:26,666
Mr. Sugawara,

369
00:23:27,416 --> 00:23:29,583
I actually have a lot of respect for you.

370
00:23:29,666 --> 00:23:31,666
[inquisitive music playing]

371
00:23:33,250 --> 00:23:35,750
[Mibu] You're smart
and a good businessman.

372
00:23:37,375 --> 00:23:38,458
And us…

373
00:23:39,916 --> 00:23:43,708
So far nobody amounts to shit around here.
We're a bunch of half-assed street thugs.

374
00:23:46,083 --> 00:23:48,541
If we're ever going to get real power,

375
00:23:49,708 --> 00:23:51,375
we're gonna need you to help us.

376
00:23:54,500 --> 00:23:55,833
Time to join us.

377
00:23:57,916 --> 00:23:59,125
[Inukai] No way!

378
00:23:59,208 --> 00:24:01,041
You've got to be kidding!

379
00:24:01,666 --> 00:24:03,500
Ten years of my life you took,

380
00:24:03,583 --> 00:24:05,791
and you've got the balls
to spout that shit?

381
00:24:05,875 --> 00:24:07,750
You chose to kill that girl, Inukai.

382
00:24:07,833 --> 00:24:09,375
[breathing heavily]

383
00:24:10,458 --> 00:24:11,583
[Mibu] Think about it.

384
00:24:13,625 --> 00:24:15,583
Don't get mad at the wrong guy.

385
00:24:19,666 --> 00:24:21,916
I'm Kyogoku's good little lapdog.

386
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:24,791
I'm just like you,
a lapdog that does what it's told.

387
00:24:26,583 --> 00:24:27,583
But one day…

388
00:24:29,916 --> 00:24:32,791
I'm gonna take off my collar
and give it back to him.

389
00:24:34,041 --> 00:24:34,916
[Inukai grunts]

390
00:24:38,041 --> 00:24:39,250
Everyone…

391
00:24:41,541 --> 00:24:43,041
Together, we'll be strong.

392
00:24:45,083 --> 00:24:46,500
[music fades]

393
00:24:51,500 --> 00:24:52,333
[horn honks]

394
00:24:54,958 --> 00:24:56,833
[Kyogoku] Mr. Karasuma.

395
00:25:07,583 --> 00:25:09,250
You gonna meet with a client in there?

396
00:25:09,333 --> 00:25:10,166
[Karasuma] I am.

397
00:25:10,250 --> 00:25:14,500
I just delivered some food to the boss.
Grilled eel on rice.

398
00:25:14,583 --> 00:25:15,583
Is that so?

399
00:25:16,208 --> 00:25:18,708
I heard you and Mr. Kujo
parted ways recently.

400
00:25:18,791 --> 00:25:20,583
You guys fight or what?

401
00:25:20,666 --> 00:25:22,166
You keeping tabs on your lawyer?

402
00:25:22,250 --> 00:25:26,458
He's my guardian angel.
I have to know everything about Mr. Kujo.

403
00:25:26,541 --> 00:25:28,083
Guardian angel, huh?

404
00:25:28,166 --> 00:25:29,458
Your closer, right?

405
00:25:29,541 --> 00:25:30,875
Your fixer, more like.

406
00:25:30,958 --> 00:25:31,875
[chuckles]

407
00:25:31,958 --> 00:25:35,291
Time for you to make a clean getaway,
Mr. Karasuma?

408
00:25:36,708 --> 00:25:38,000
It doesn't matter what you say.

409
00:25:38,083 --> 00:25:42,458
Look, kid. You're still young,
so let me tell you how the world works.

410
00:25:43,208 --> 00:25:45,458
Even when you're sure
you've made your escape,

411
00:25:45,541 --> 00:25:47,625
once you've got some mud on you,

412
00:25:47,708 --> 00:25:48,916
when you least expect it,

413
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:51,875
a bloody hand will reach up
from the ground and grab you.

414
00:25:52,666 --> 00:25:53,958
Like the movie <i>Carrie.</i>

415
00:25:54,666 --> 00:25:55,666
<i>Carrie?</i>

416
00:25:56,208 --> 00:25:58,000
De Palma's greatest achievement.

417
00:25:58,666 --> 00:26:00,666
You've gotta keep your eyes open.

418
00:26:00,750 --> 00:26:01,791
You'll see.

419
00:26:02,541 --> 00:26:05,208
Someday, the bodies of people
you don't even remember

420
00:26:05,291 --> 00:26:08,000
will come crawling out,
and then they'll come looking for you.

421
00:26:14,541 --> 00:26:17,000
Everyone likes to think
their sins just fade away.

422
00:26:17,916 --> 00:26:20,208
But when you're not looking,
they get bigger.

423
00:26:21,250 --> 00:26:22,875
Running only makes it worse.

424
00:26:25,250 --> 00:26:26,708
I've gotta go.

425
00:26:26,791 --> 00:26:27,791
Shinji!

426
00:26:31,916 --> 00:26:33,875
Take good care of your family.

427
00:26:33,958 --> 00:26:35,958
[ominous music playing]

428
00:26:41,916 --> 00:26:43,375
[music fades]

429
00:26:43,458 --> 00:26:44,750
[yells]

430
00:26:45,625 --> 00:26:47,583
- Hey! Wait!
- [thugs laughing]

431
00:26:47,666 --> 00:26:49,541
- Hey! Hey, hey! Hold it there!
- [thug] Woo!

432
00:26:49,625 --> 00:26:51,333
Destruction of property. You're coming in.

433
00:26:51,416 --> 00:26:53,166
[Morita] Shut up, you bastard!

434
00:26:53,250 --> 00:26:55,208
- Hey, wait a minute!
- [thug] Get out of my way!

435
00:26:55,875 --> 00:26:58,375
- Just stop it! Hey!
- What's up with you?

436
00:26:58,458 --> 00:27:00,791
- Are you tweaking or what?
- Of course not, asshole!

437
00:27:00,875 --> 00:27:02,250
- Ow!
- [cop] Stop resisting!

438
00:27:02,333 --> 00:27:04,458
- [thug] Get your stinking hands off me!
- That hurts! Ow!

439
00:27:04,541 --> 00:27:05,541
Ouch, ow, ow!

440
00:27:05,625 --> 00:27:06,791
That hurts!

441
00:27:06,875 --> 00:27:09,958
- [cop] Shut up and stop resisting.
- You asshole. Call the police! Help!

442
00:27:17,583 --> 00:27:20,041
What's wrong? You look a little down.

443
00:27:23,541 --> 00:27:25,416
Is it true that I ran away?

444
00:27:26,375 --> 00:27:27,333
Huh?

445
00:27:28,125 --> 00:27:29,500
I was told I ran away

446
00:27:30,375 --> 00:27:32,583
from the Yakuza who is close to Mr. Kujo.

447
00:27:34,458 --> 00:27:35,916
I've always known about it.

448
00:27:37,250 --> 00:27:40,875
His clients are involved
in multiple cases of fraud and extortion.

449
00:27:41,541 --> 00:27:45,083
There's a high risk of him being arrested
and charged as an accomplice.

450
00:27:46,625 --> 00:27:49,500
If he were prosecuted and convicted
of a criminal offense,

451
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:51,500
he'd lose his job for good.

452
00:27:52,375 --> 00:27:55,083
Even if he avoided a trial,
he'd still be disciplined.

453
00:27:55,958 --> 00:27:58,083
And in the worst case,
he could be disbarred.

454
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:03,333
[Nagaragi] I understand your concern,
Karasuma,

455
00:28:03,416 --> 00:28:05,125
but it's Kujo we're talking about.

456
00:28:05,625 --> 00:28:09,333
I'm sure he's being very careful
to stay out of trouble.

457
00:28:09,833 --> 00:28:12,375
What if there's a prosecutor
who's dead set against him?

458
00:28:12,458 --> 00:28:14,041
Couldn't Mr. Kujo end up in jail?

459
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:16,750
Dead set against him?

460
00:28:16,833 --> 00:28:18,208
Is there a prosecutor like that?

461
00:28:20,666 --> 00:28:21,583
Who knows?

462
00:28:22,083 --> 00:28:24,083
[upbeat music playing]

463
00:28:25,375 --> 00:28:27,291
[man] That's some good press, Kurama.

464
00:28:27,375 --> 00:28:28,458
Nice work.

465
00:28:29,166 --> 00:28:30,375
No, sir.

466
00:28:30,458 --> 00:28:33,375
Your formulation of the hypothesis
was a stroke of genius.

467
00:28:33,458 --> 00:28:35,708
[man] My hunch was mostly right.
That was all.

468
00:28:35,791 --> 00:28:38,708
One thing you can be sure of,
crooks like this,

469
00:28:38,791 --> 00:28:41,250
they only care about taking
what they can get.

470
00:28:41,333 --> 00:28:43,625
[Kurama] That's true
of bad people everywhere.

471
00:28:45,708 --> 00:28:49,625
Even some prosecutors are starting
to act like selfish corporate types.

472
00:28:50,541 --> 00:28:53,666
But not you. I like your tenacity.

473
00:28:54,458 --> 00:28:55,791
Thank you very much.

474
00:28:55,875 --> 00:28:58,958
Now that Ono has quit,
you're the only one I can rely on.

475
00:28:59,041 --> 00:29:00,333
I'm counting on you.

476
00:29:02,708 --> 00:29:06,583
And have you heard about what
Mr. Ono intends to do when he retires?

477
00:29:06,666 --> 00:29:09,166
[man] Private practice, I think.
A lawyer-for-hire.

478
00:29:10,750 --> 00:29:12,041
I don't like lawyers.

479
00:29:12,833 --> 00:29:13,916
Especially

480
00:29:14,833 --> 00:29:16,500
ones who protect bad people.

481
00:29:16,583 --> 00:29:17,791
I detest them.

482
00:29:17,875 --> 00:29:18,875
[music fades]

483
00:29:19,458 --> 00:29:22,583
[Karasuma] Sorry. I kept saying I'd treat
you, and I didn't get around to it.

484
00:29:23,416 --> 00:29:24,833
I can pay for this.

485
00:29:24,916 --> 00:29:28,291
No. It's fine.
You can pick up the tab at a better place.

486
00:29:28,916 --> 00:29:30,458
I won some money at the races,

487
00:29:30,541 --> 00:29:33,250
and I wanted to thank you
for introducing me to Ms. Ichida.

488
00:29:33,333 --> 00:29:34,541
She said she'd join us later.

489
00:29:34,625 --> 00:29:36,625
[indistinct chatter]

490
00:29:37,125 --> 00:29:39,791
Mmm! This is good. You chose a great spot.

491
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:44,041
How come you quit working for Mr. Kujo?

492
00:29:44,125 --> 00:29:45,000
Huh?

493
00:29:45,083 --> 00:29:46,958
I'm the one
who introduced you to him, right?

494
00:29:47,041 --> 00:29:50,291
And yet you quit without even
consulting me or telling me about it.

495
00:29:50,375 --> 00:29:53,333
You're barely fit to be
a member of society, let alone a lawyer.

496
00:29:53,833 --> 00:29:54,750
I'm sorry.

497
00:29:56,208 --> 00:29:57,458
So what happened?

498
00:29:58,541 --> 00:30:00,291
I thought that if I stayed with Mr. Kujo,

499
00:30:00,875 --> 00:30:05,000
I'd never end up doing what
I really should be doing with my life.

500
00:30:06,250 --> 00:30:07,125
Oh.

501
00:30:08,166 --> 00:30:09,458
So that means

502
00:30:09,958 --> 00:30:12,458
you have at least some idea
of what to do with your life.

503
00:30:13,625 --> 00:30:16,583
Sure. It's the same for you, isn't it?
As a social worker.

504
00:30:18,833 --> 00:30:19,958
Somehow,

505
00:30:21,125 --> 00:30:22,958
I've been losing sight of it lately.

506
00:30:24,333 --> 00:30:25,500
Did something happen?

507
00:30:27,625 --> 00:30:31,916
Listen. As lawyers,
you and Mr. Kujo use the law to…

508
00:30:32,958 --> 00:30:36,208
to defend the rights of the weak, right?

509
00:30:36,958 --> 00:30:37,791
Well…

510
00:30:37,875 --> 00:30:40,000
And Ms. Ichida, the newspaper reporter,

511
00:30:40,708 --> 00:30:44,416
uncovers the truth about social problems
and shares it with the public

512
00:30:45,083 --> 00:30:47,750
to stop those things from happening
and to protect society.

513
00:30:47,833 --> 00:30:48,791
Yeah. You're right.

514
00:30:48,875 --> 00:30:50,833
So what should I be protecting?

515
00:30:51,625 --> 00:30:52,750
Well, as a social worker,

516
00:30:52,833 --> 00:30:54,916
you help rehabilitate people
who have committed crimes.

517
00:30:55,000 --> 00:30:57,833
Yeah, but is that even protecting them
from anything?

518
00:30:57,916 --> 00:30:58,750
Yeah.

519
00:30:58,833 --> 00:31:00,500
Wouldn't it be more productive

520
00:31:00,583 --> 00:31:04,166
if I could prevent them from committing
their crimes in the first place?

521
00:31:05,291 --> 00:31:06,208
Well…

522
00:31:07,333 --> 00:31:09,916
I mean, what am I doing for them?

523
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:11,833
Should I be helping them
get over their past

524
00:31:11,916 --> 00:31:13,041
or stay safe in the future?

525
00:31:13,125 --> 00:31:14,250
How do you do that?

526
00:31:15,250 --> 00:31:17,041
How can I actually do some good?

527
00:31:19,625 --> 00:31:21,125
What am I going to protect?

528
00:31:28,458 --> 00:31:30,458
[cell phone buzzes]

529
00:31:34,166 --> 00:31:36,333
Hello, Ms. Ichida?
Are you able to make it?

530
00:31:36,416 --> 00:31:39,000
[Ichida] Uh, I'm sorry.
I'm still staking out the prosecutor…

531
00:31:39,083 --> 00:31:40,666
Uh, it's gonna be a long night.

532
00:31:40,750 --> 00:31:41,958
Maybe next time.

533
00:31:42,875 --> 00:31:44,375
[Yakushimae] <i>What are prosecutors like?</i>

534
00:31:44,458 --> 00:31:45,875
What do they protect?

535
00:31:47,541 --> 00:31:51,250
I guess they would claim
to protect the idea of justice?

536
00:31:51,916 --> 00:31:54,250
Even so, I can't stand those guys.

537
00:31:54,333 --> 00:31:55,458
How come?

538
00:31:55,958 --> 00:32:00,125
The legal system in this country
follows the rule of exclusive prosecution.

539
00:32:00,208 --> 00:32:02,083
Wait, run that by me again?

540
00:32:02,666 --> 00:32:03,708
It works like this.

541
00:32:04,250 --> 00:32:07,500
Only the prosecution has the authority
to seek justice against criminals.

542
00:32:08,250 --> 00:32:11,208
<i>In other words, if the prosecution decides</i>
<i>not to proceed to trial,</i>

543
00:32:11,291 --> 00:32:13,000
<i>it's the same as being acquitted.</i>

544
00:32:13,666 --> 00:32:16,458
<i>So they have the authority</i>
<i>to decide people's fates.</i>

545
00:32:16,541 --> 00:32:17,666
[inquisitive music playing]

546
00:32:17,750 --> 00:32:18,666
I get it.

547
00:32:20,625 --> 00:32:22,541
I really don't like those guys.

548
00:32:27,291 --> 00:32:29,166
Good evening, Prosecutor Kurama.

549
00:32:29,666 --> 00:32:32,125
Your article on the contractors
was excellent.

550
00:32:32,208 --> 00:32:33,791
My superior liked it too.

551
00:32:33,875 --> 00:32:36,208
Thanks for all your help.
The scoop was amazing.

552
00:32:36,291 --> 00:32:37,791
Thank you very much.

553
00:32:37,875 --> 00:32:41,458
You cover stories that conjure up
strong emotions to reach your readers.

554
00:32:43,541 --> 00:32:46,416
I have more leads like this.
You want them, right?

555
00:32:49,375 --> 00:32:50,958
What's wrong? Don't you want them?

556
00:32:51,458 --> 00:32:52,708
Prosecutor Kurama.

557
00:32:55,500 --> 00:32:58,500
Taiza Kujo, your brother, I mean,

558
00:32:58,583 --> 00:33:00,958
has been meeting with the boss
of the Fushimi-gumi.

559
00:33:01,875 --> 00:33:05,166
It's almost as if he's acting
like their lawyer on retainer.

560
00:33:07,375 --> 00:33:08,500
One more thing.

561
00:33:09,375 --> 00:33:12,666
One of Mr. Kujo's former clients,
serving a suspended sentence,

562
00:33:12,750 --> 00:33:14,083
was re-arrested for drugs.

563
00:33:14,166 --> 00:33:16,625
This suspect was sent
to Detective Arashiyama

564
00:33:16,708 --> 00:33:17,833
of the Organized Crime squad.

565
00:33:18,500 --> 00:33:20,000
Arashiyama, was it?

566
00:33:21,166 --> 00:33:22,166
Do you know him?

567
00:33:23,166 --> 00:33:25,125
We worked together on the case of a woman

568
00:33:25,208 --> 00:33:26,833
who was killed and dismembered.

569
00:33:26,916 --> 00:33:29,375
He's the kind of cop who stops at nothing.

570
00:33:30,708 --> 00:33:32,708
Did you know that
his daughter was murdered?

571
00:33:32,791 --> 00:33:33,666
I'm aware.

572
00:33:34,166 --> 00:33:36,916
For years he's been convinced
that the Fushimi-gumi is behind it.

573
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:39,458
After all this time,
he's still working that angle.

574
00:33:39,541 --> 00:33:41,625
In his effort to take
down the Fushimi-gumi,

575
00:33:41,708 --> 00:33:43,791
Detective Arashiyama
seems to be after Mr. Kujo.

576
00:33:43,875 --> 00:33:46,375
Arashiyama's assessment has its strengths.

577
00:33:47,625 --> 00:33:51,791
It looks like Taiza's career
as a lawyer could finally be over.

578
00:33:52,416 --> 00:33:54,416
What are you going to do about all this?

579
00:33:56,541 --> 00:33:59,041
Continue your coverage. It's a scoop.

580
00:34:00,541 --> 00:34:01,500
Ms. Ichida,

581
00:34:02,458 --> 00:34:05,000
you cover stories that
conjure up strong emotions,

582
00:34:05,958 --> 00:34:07,750
that reach your readers.

583
00:34:07,833 --> 00:34:09,666
[music fades]

584
00:34:20,625 --> 00:34:21,500
[laughs]

585
00:34:21,583 --> 00:34:23,583
[cell phone buzzes]

586
00:34:28,791 --> 00:34:29,625
What's wrong?

587
00:34:30,375 --> 00:34:32,875
[Mibu] <i>This stupid kid I know got busted.</i>

588
00:34:32,958 --> 00:34:34,166
<i>Can you help me with it?</i>

589
00:34:35,916 --> 00:34:37,958
The guy's a hopeless scumbag,

590
00:34:38,583 --> 00:34:41,500
but his father runs a construction firm
I do business with,

591
00:34:41,583 --> 00:34:43,708
<i>so I have to babysit the asshole.</i>

592
00:34:45,333 --> 00:34:46,166
Could it be…

593
00:34:47,458 --> 00:34:50,458
The product of really bad
parenting choices.

594
00:34:50,541 --> 00:34:51,750
[tense music playing]

595
00:34:51,833 --> 00:34:54,791
[Arashiyama] You're gonna clam up again,
Morita?

596
00:34:55,541 --> 00:34:57,625
Your urine test came back positive.

597
00:34:57,708 --> 00:35:00,291
You can't weasel out of this.
Cough up the truth.

598
00:35:04,583 --> 00:35:06,625
You know,
there's something I wanna ask you,

599
00:35:06,708 --> 00:35:07,875
Morita, old pal.

600
00:35:07,958 --> 00:35:10,541
In your previous statement
about the hit-and-run,

601
00:35:10,625 --> 00:35:12,791
you swore that you lost your smartphone.

602
00:35:14,833 --> 00:35:15,916
Uh, uh… Yeah.

603
00:35:20,375 --> 00:35:23,125
Seems like you got a pretty old
smartphone, wouldn't you say?

604
00:35:23,208 --> 00:35:24,166
Huh?

605
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:27,166
What if this is the smartphone you lost?

606
00:35:28,791 --> 00:35:31,625
- I found it under my bed.
- [Arashiyama] Don't lie to me.

607
00:35:32,208 --> 00:35:34,458
Back then,
you pretended to lose it, right?

608
00:35:36,583 --> 00:35:38,333
It wasn't your idea, was it?

609
00:35:38,833 --> 00:35:41,625
Did Attorney Kujo coach you?
Did he tell you to say you lost it?

610
00:35:48,125 --> 00:35:50,416
If you talk I'll cut down your sentence,

611
00:35:50,500 --> 00:35:53,000
so give me all of it, Morita.

612
00:35:55,250 --> 00:35:56,458
[upbeat music playing]

613
00:35:58,000 --> 00:35:59,458
Get a suspended sentence?

614
00:35:59,958 --> 00:36:01,250
Can't you just try?

615
00:36:01,833 --> 00:36:03,375
[Kujo] Probably impossible.

616
00:36:03,875 --> 00:36:05,791
Your urine tested positive for drugs.

617
00:36:05,875 --> 00:36:09,833
You also had MDMA,
that's three pills, about a gram in total.

618
00:36:09,916 --> 00:36:11,500
That's beside the property damage.

619
00:36:13,750 --> 00:36:15,833
No way.

620
00:36:16,750 --> 00:36:18,333
I'm going to prison?

621
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:22,750
Mr. Morita, you were serving
a suspended sentence

622
00:36:22,833 --> 00:36:25,208
for a traffic accident,
and you reoffended.

623
00:36:30,958 --> 00:36:32,291
Just clam up in there.

624
00:36:37,833 --> 00:36:38,916
Was there a problem?

625
00:36:42,625 --> 00:36:46,791
Detective, how can we prove that
Morita left his phone at Kujo's office?

626
00:36:47,541 --> 00:36:49,208
We need three things.

627
00:36:49,875 --> 00:36:53,250
First of all, we need Morita
to sign a statement declaring

628
00:36:53,333 --> 00:36:55,000
that Kujo told him to leave it there.

629
00:36:55,083 --> 00:36:58,583
We dangled the bait of a reduced sentence,
so if we work him a bit more, he'll talk.

630
00:36:58,666 --> 00:36:59,833
What's the second thing?

631
00:37:00,416 --> 00:37:02,458
Matching testimony from another witness.

632
00:37:02,541 --> 00:37:04,458
We will corroborate Morita's statement,

633
00:37:04,541 --> 00:37:06,541
then the whole thing
starts to be credible.

634
00:37:07,375 --> 00:37:09,708
Some hard evidence is
the third thing we need.

635
00:37:11,041 --> 00:37:13,208
Were you able to get
the phone's location data?

636
00:37:13,291 --> 00:37:14,125
Yes.

637
00:37:14,208 --> 00:37:17,333
What about on the day Morita turned
himself in for the traffic accident?

638
00:37:18,291 --> 00:37:21,250
[Fukami] The address of Kujo Law Office
was in the location history.

639
00:37:21,333 --> 00:37:23,791
So that means the phone had to be there.

640
00:37:23,875 --> 00:37:24,791
I see.

641
00:37:25,833 --> 00:37:28,541
I'd call that objective evidence,
wouldn't you?

642
00:37:29,125 --> 00:37:30,041
Yeah.

643
00:37:30,125 --> 00:37:31,958
So, we've got two things covered.

644
00:37:32,041 --> 00:37:35,000
The only thing left is the testimony
from another person of interest.

645
00:37:35,083 --> 00:37:36,625
Then we'll have all three things.

646
00:37:36,708 --> 00:37:37,666
That's right.

647
00:37:38,958 --> 00:37:40,041
One more thing.

648
00:37:40,916 --> 00:37:43,833
Then Attorney Kujo will be looking at
some serious time.

649
00:37:44,333 --> 00:37:45,708
- [bell dings]
- [music fades]

650
00:37:57,750 --> 00:37:58,791
[Kujo] This is delicious.

651
00:37:58,875 --> 00:38:01,416
[Mrs. Karasuma chuckles]
I'm glad you like it.

652
00:38:01,500 --> 00:38:05,333
Oh, and you must try a bit of this too
while it's still hot.

653
00:38:05,416 --> 00:38:07,041
- [Kujo] Omurice?
- [Mrs. Karasuma] Yes.

654
00:38:07,125 --> 00:38:10,375
My dad loved this. In the Karasuma family
it's our lucky meal.

655
00:38:10,958 --> 00:38:12,791
- For this, our thanks.
- [Mrs. Karasuma] Enjoy.

656
00:38:12,875 --> 00:38:13,958
[chuckles]

657
00:38:19,750 --> 00:38:21,458
[chuckles] This is good.

658
00:38:21,541 --> 00:38:22,875
- You like it?
- Yes. Mmm.

659
00:38:23,375 --> 00:38:25,750
I love the seasoning.
Especially the ketchup rice.

660
00:38:25,833 --> 00:38:27,000
- [Mrs. Karasuma chuckles]
- Mmm.

661
00:38:27,083 --> 00:38:28,708
[Mrs. Karasuma] I've gotta say,

662
00:38:28,791 --> 00:38:31,125
you're not what I was expecting at all.

663
00:38:32,041 --> 00:38:35,041
The media refers to you
as the "crooked lawyer."

664
00:38:35,125 --> 00:38:36,916
So I really wasn't sure
who was gonna show up.

665
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:38,250
[Karasuma] Mom, please.

666
00:38:38,333 --> 00:38:39,666
Huh? What's wrong?

667
00:38:39,750 --> 00:38:41,875
I'm just giving him a compliment.

668
00:38:41,958 --> 00:38:43,958
She's giving me a compliment.

669
00:38:44,041 --> 00:38:46,416
- [Karasuma sighs]
- [laughs]

670
00:38:47,125 --> 00:38:49,875
I can tell you're a good person, Mr. Kujo.

671
00:38:49,958 --> 00:38:50,791
How so?

672
00:38:51,375 --> 00:38:55,041
Someone who enjoys their food
like you do could never be a bad person.

673
00:38:55,125 --> 00:38:57,041
[both chuckle]

674
00:38:57,125 --> 00:38:59,208
- Please. Enjoy. Eat up.
- [Kujo] Okay.

675
00:38:59,291 --> 00:39:00,958
- [Mrs. Karasuma] Yes. Eat, eat.
- Thank you.

676
00:39:03,833 --> 00:39:05,416
This reminds me of your dad.

677
00:39:06,291 --> 00:39:08,958
He used to make coffee for us
after dinner like this.

678
00:39:09,041 --> 00:39:10,375
He did, didn't he?

679
00:39:10,875 --> 00:39:15,000
Mmm. He'd say, "Coffee is my specialty."

680
00:39:16,833 --> 00:39:17,916
I sure do miss him.

681
00:39:28,708 --> 00:39:29,916
Mr. Kujo.

682
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:31,041
Yes?

683
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:34,958
You know,
ever since my husband passed away,

684
00:39:35,041 --> 00:39:36,250
for the longest time,

685
00:39:37,625 --> 00:39:41,458
I used to get numb with sadness
thinking about the past.

686
00:39:43,666 --> 00:39:48,250
But I think now…
I'm finally rounding a corner.

687
00:39:49,583 --> 00:39:52,333
Somehow,
I'm starting to feel things again.

688
00:39:54,791 --> 00:39:57,250
All his life,
your dad was the kind of person

689
00:39:57,333 --> 00:40:00,250
who felt compelled to help people in need.

690
00:40:01,875 --> 00:40:04,291
That's what he was doing
when he was killed

691
00:40:04,375 --> 00:40:07,500
trying to defend that passenger
who was being attacked.

692
00:40:09,625 --> 00:40:11,541
But even in his last moments…

693
00:40:14,166 --> 00:40:16,500
I don't think he had any regrets.

694
00:40:19,958 --> 00:40:22,833
I think the way he died was
also the way he lived.

695
00:40:23,416 --> 00:40:25,416
[melancholy music playing]

696
00:40:29,541 --> 00:40:30,458
Here you go.

697
00:40:31,916 --> 00:40:33,208
Thank you very much.

698
00:40:33,291 --> 00:40:34,791
Thank you for the coffee.

699
00:40:42,708 --> 00:40:43,625
[Karasuma sighs]

700
00:40:43,708 --> 00:40:47,291
Mmm! It's delicious. [chuckles]

701
00:40:47,375 --> 00:40:48,458
I'm glad you like it.

702
00:40:53,750 --> 00:40:55,916
Mr. Kujo, I imagine your parents

703
00:40:56,958 --> 00:40:59,916
would be proud to see how
much you've accomplished.

704
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:02,000
[Kujo chuckles] I wonder about that.

705
00:41:02,083 --> 00:41:05,625
It was always my mother's dream
for me to become a prosecutor.

706
00:41:06,750 --> 00:41:10,041
But I wasn't as talented
as my father or older brother.

707
00:41:10,125 --> 00:41:11,416
I kept failing the bar exam,

708
00:41:11,500 --> 00:41:13,875
and there were times
when I thought about giving up.

709
00:41:14,708 --> 00:41:16,458
But even at my lowest,

710
00:41:16,541 --> 00:41:19,333
I wanted to have something
that only I could do.

711
00:41:21,666 --> 00:41:24,958
My mother passed away when I was
in my first year of high school,

712
00:41:25,958 --> 00:41:29,333
but she always said I should try to become
someone who helps others.

713
00:41:30,916 --> 00:41:34,333
Even a person like me,
despite my lack of talent,

714
00:41:34,416 --> 00:41:36,375
can help others and give them hope.

715
00:41:37,458 --> 00:41:40,333
I still sincerely believe that
I've got to see it through to the end.

716
00:41:44,333 --> 00:41:47,250
I wish I could've told my mother
when she was still alive.

717
00:41:49,958 --> 00:41:51,875
I chose not to be a prosecutor.

718
00:41:52,791 --> 00:41:54,333
I chose to be a lawyer.

719
00:41:59,375 --> 00:42:01,250
[Mrs. Karasuma] If that's
what you want to do,

720
00:42:01,333 --> 00:42:03,541
I'll support you with all my heart.

721
00:42:06,375 --> 00:42:07,333
There.

722
00:42:08,625 --> 00:42:10,958
I know that's what your mother would say.

723
00:42:23,250 --> 00:42:24,375
[Karasuma] Mr. Kujo?

724
00:42:36,750 --> 00:42:38,375
[music fades]

725
00:42:43,791 --> 00:42:45,291
[door opens]

726
00:42:49,958 --> 00:42:52,458
[Mibu] Mr. Kujo, do you have a moment?

727
00:42:52,541 --> 00:42:54,375
[exhales deeply]

728
00:42:59,458 --> 00:43:00,416
Should I come back?

729
00:43:01,000 --> 00:43:01,916
No.

730
00:43:02,958 --> 00:43:04,416
How can I help?

731
00:43:04,500 --> 00:43:05,583
Yes.

732
00:43:05,666 --> 00:43:08,500
Mm-hmm. Yes. Please hold on a moment.

733
00:43:09,666 --> 00:43:10,916
Mr. Karasuma.

734
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:11,833
Yes?

735
00:43:11,916 --> 00:43:14,250
A Honjo Police Station
detective calling for you.

736
00:43:14,333 --> 00:43:15,500
[Karasuma] Of course, sir.

737
00:43:17,416 --> 00:43:18,500
[sighs]

738
00:43:19,291 --> 00:43:21,875
Hello. This is Karasuma.
Who am I speaking to?

739
00:43:22,958 --> 00:43:24,958
<i>Hello, my name's Arashiyama.</i>

740
00:43:25,458 --> 00:43:27,791
I know this is a rather unusual request.

741
00:43:27,875 --> 00:43:30,125
I'd like to ask you about a few things.

742
00:43:32,208 --> 00:43:36,916
Would you mind coming down
to the police station, Mr. Karasuma?

743
00:43:37,500 --> 00:43:40,458
Morita's getting pressured by Arashiyama.
I'm worried about it.

744
00:43:40,541 --> 00:43:41,583
[upbeat music playing]

745
00:43:41,666 --> 00:43:44,500
In chess terms,
what is Detective Arashiyama up to?

746
00:43:44,583 --> 00:43:47,458
He's attacking Morita, a pawn,
to take down the two of us,

747
00:43:47,541 --> 00:43:49,291
that is, a rook and a bishop,

748
00:43:49,375 --> 00:43:51,458
so he can get to Kyogoku, the king.

749
00:43:52,041 --> 00:43:54,500
What if Morita, a pawn,
crosses to the other side

750
00:43:54,583 --> 00:43:55,500
and gets promoted?

751
00:43:55,583 --> 00:43:56,708
It would take a lot of guts

752
00:43:56,791 --> 00:44:00,250
for the police to conduct a compulsory
investigation of a law office.

753
00:44:01,208 --> 00:44:03,250
To pursue that approach,
they need solid evidence.

754
00:44:05,500 --> 00:44:06,375
However,

755
00:44:07,833 --> 00:44:10,625
if they really believe
they can put us into checkmate,

756
00:44:12,166 --> 00:44:14,291
they'll throw everything
they've got at us.

757
00:44:20,708 --> 00:44:21,833
[Fukami] Mr. Karasuma,

758
00:44:22,583 --> 00:44:25,375
would you mind showing us
your cell phone for a moment?

759
00:44:25,458 --> 00:44:26,416
Why?

760
00:44:26,500 --> 00:44:29,166
To make sure you're not recording
this conversation.

761
00:44:33,000 --> 00:44:34,083
Here you go.

762
00:44:38,208 --> 00:44:39,583
So, what do you want?

763
00:44:40,208 --> 00:44:44,750
Why did you decide to stop working
at Kujo Law Office, Mr. Karasuma?

764
00:44:45,375 --> 00:44:46,833
For personal reasons.

765
00:44:47,541 --> 00:44:49,916
Surely you don't need me
to go into the details.

766
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:52,416
Was it because
you were sick of how Mr. Kujo

767
00:44:52,500 --> 00:44:54,250
was always mixed up with criminals?

768
00:44:54,750 --> 00:44:56,375
[chuckles]

769
00:44:56,458 --> 00:44:59,875
Amazing how police detectives
always jump to conclusions.

770
00:44:59,958 --> 00:45:01,208
All right.

771
00:45:02,083 --> 00:45:03,791
It's true, isn't it,

772
00:45:03,875 --> 00:45:06,416
that you saw Morita,
one of Kujo's clients,

773
00:45:06,500 --> 00:45:09,708
hand over his phone in the office
when he was receiving legal counsel.

774
00:45:10,708 --> 00:45:11,750
What are you talking about?

775
00:45:11,833 --> 00:45:13,583
Morita just admitted it.

776
00:45:16,125 --> 00:45:19,875
On the advice of Mr. Kujo,
my phone was left in his law office.

777
00:45:20,375 --> 00:45:21,666
That's right.

778
00:45:23,625 --> 00:45:28,375
The address of Kujo Law Office was found
in the location history of his phone

779
00:45:28,458 --> 00:45:31,375
on the day Morita turned himself in
for the hit-and-run.

780
00:45:31,458 --> 00:45:33,708
That's a clear case of
concealing evidence.

781
00:45:33,791 --> 00:45:36,791
He came for a consultation.
Of course the address is in the history.

782
00:45:36,875 --> 00:45:40,666
Mr. Karasuma, what do you got there?
That's a pen that records, isn't it?

783
00:45:42,083 --> 00:45:45,208
I've seen one of those gizmos before,
so I noticed it.

784
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:48,333
You came prepared, like a good boy scout.

785
00:45:48,416 --> 00:45:51,750
Who knows when you might be subjected
to an unlawful interrogation?

786
00:45:54,166 --> 00:45:57,000
Did you also happen
to record the conversation

787
00:45:57,083 --> 00:45:58,875
between Mr. Kujo and Morita?

788
00:45:59,833 --> 00:46:02,208
If that's the case,
didn't you hear the instructions

789
00:46:02,291 --> 00:46:04,208
from Mr. Kujo to conceal the evidence?

790
00:46:05,083 --> 00:46:07,375
Surely, you weren't an accomplice,
were you?

791
00:46:08,750 --> 00:46:11,583
Mr. Kujo was just doing
what any good lawyer would do.

792
00:46:11,666 --> 00:46:16,833
Mr. Karasuma, if you try to cover for him,
you'll end up being disbarred with him.

793
00:46:17,958 --> 00:46:19,458
Are you okay with that?

794
00:46:19,958 --> 00:46:21,875
Wouldn't that upset your mother?

795
00:46:22,583 --> 00:46:25,208
- She's got nothing to do with this.
- [Fukami] That's not true.

796
00:46:25,791 --> 00:46:28,708
If the story gets around
that you're a crooked lawyer,

797
00:46:28,791 --> 00:46:31,958
then people will say you really are
a family of degenerates.

798
00:46:32,041 --> 00:46:33,000
My family?

799
00:46:35,208 --> 00:46:36,291
What do you mean by that?

800
00:46:36,375 --> 00:46:37,541
[Fukami] What do I mean?

801
00:46:37,625 --> 00:46:40,291
I mean your father, the pervert.

802
00:46:41,166 --> 00:46:43,083
Sure, I could remind the public

803
00:46:43,166 --> 00:46:46,583
by having another article written
about what kind of man he was.

804
00:46:46,666 --> 00:46:48,041
[Arashiyama] Fukami, cut it out.

805
00:46:48,958 --> 00:46:49,875
For years now,

806
00:46:49,958 --> 00:46:53,750
Mr. Karasuma's family has been going
through hell because of that article.

807
00:46:55,250 --> 00:46:58,500
I apologize for his behavior.
That was rude of him.

808
00:47:00,291 --> 00:47:01,416
But it must be obvious.

809
00:47:01,500 --> 00:47:04,208
If we called in a lawyer
in this unorthodox way,

810
00:47:04,291 --> 00:47:08,208
it shows we're pursuing this investigation
with a certain level of commitment.

811
00:47:12,833 --> 00:47:16,333
If you give us a statement,
we can get to Kyogoku.

812
00:47:18,916 --> 00:47:21,083
You're the last piece of the puzzle.

813
00:47:22,541 --> 00:47:26,416
You can help save the weakest people
who are suffering because of those crooks.

814
00:47:29,125 --> 00:47:30,833
Let's put an end to this.

815
00:47:33,208 --> 00:47:35,208
[tense music playing]

816
00:47:37,750 --> 00:47:39,375
INUKAI

817
00:47:41,166 --> 00:47:42,041
Excuse me.

818
00:47:43,541 --> 00:47:44,500
[sighs]

819
00:47:45,791 --> 00:47:47,041
What is it, Inukai?

820
00:47:47,125 --> 00:47:48,833
I just kidnapped a guy.

821
00:47:49,416 --> 00:47:50,833
I worked him over good.

822
00:47:50,916 --> 00:47:53,291
Someone asked me to.
What should I do with him?

823
00:47:54,708 --> 00:47:55,958
Is this someone you know?

824
00:47:56,041 --> 00:47:57,500
Never met the guy.

825
00:47:59,625 --> 00:48:02,125
I grabbed him
where the security cameras don't see.

826
00:48:02,833 --> 00:48:04,000
<i>So, it's all good.</i>

827
00:48:04,791 --> 00:48:06,041
Then get rid of him somewhere.

828
00:48:06,791 --> 00:48:08,083
Just in case, lie low.

829
00:48:08,166 --> 00:48:10,041
Yes, Mr. Mibu.

830
00:48:11,000 --> 00:48:13,000
[Mibu] <i>Turn off your phone</i>
<i>after you hang up.</i>

831
00:48:13,666 --> 00:48:14,500
Huh?

832
00:48:15,083 --> 00:48:17,875
I don't want the police to pick up
the location signals.

833
00:48:18,958 --> 00:48:20,041
Don't just turn it off.

834
00:48:20,125 --> 00:48:22,833
Remove the SIM card and stash it
somewhere away from the phone.

835
00:48:23,666 --> 00:48:24,750
Oh. Okay.

836
00:48:24,833 --> 00:48:25,958
[Mibu] <i>When things cool down,</i>

837
00:48:26,041 --> 00:48:28,500
turn on your phone
while you're driving on the highway.

838
00:48:28,583 --> 00:48:29,833
[Inukai] <i>Got it.</i>

839
00:48:32,875 --> 00:48:35,458
You and me,
always getting into trouble, aren't we?

840
00:48:35,958 --> 00:48:36,791
I'll say.

841
00:48:39,166 --> 00:48:41,166
[cell phone buzzing]

842
00:48:44,583 --> 00:48:45,416
Excuse me again.

843
00:48:52,000 --> 00:48:52,833
Yes?

844
00:48:53,416 --> 00:48:54,583
[Kyogoku] Mibu.

845
00:48:54,666 --> 00:48:58,708
Listen. I just heard from my wife.
She said our son is nowhere to be found.

846
00:48:58,791 --> 00:48:59,833
You know anything?

847
00:49:00,416 --> 00:49:02,250
<i>Haven't been able to reach him</i>
<i>since last night.</i>

848
00:49:02,333 --> 00:49:04,333
<i>It's probably no big deal, but…</i>

849
00:49:05,000 --> 00:49:07,833
[groans]

850
00:49:08,541 --> 00:49:09,875
No, nothing on my end.

851
00:49:09,958 --> 00:49:10,958
I see.

852
00:49:11,041 --> 00:49:12,541
Get back to me if you hear something.

853
00:49:12,625 --> 00:49:13,541
Okay.

854
00:49:13,625 --> 00:49:15,666
[tense music playing]

855
00:49:21,833 --> 00:49:23,875
[line beeps]

856
00:49:24,666 --> 00:49:26,166
[operator] <i>The person you are trying…</i>

857
00:49:26,250 --> 00:49:29,291
Damn it!
Inukai turned off his phone already.

858
00:49:30,875 --> 00:49:32,000
[sighs]

859
00:49:33,583 --> 00:49:35,583
[cell phone rings]

860
00:49:37,916 --> 00:49:39,875
Mibu, what's up?

861
00:49:39,958 --> 00:49:41,083
Some serious shit, Kuga.

862
00:49:41,166 --> 00:49:42,083
Find Inukai.

863
00:49:42,875 --> 00:49:45,041
I wanna know who the hell
that idiot kidnapped.

864
00:49:46,958 --> 00:49:49,166
[grunting, groaning]

865
00:49:49,250 --> 00:49:51,041
[Komatsu] What are we gonna do with him?

866
00:49:51,125 --> 00:49:53,000
We'll dump him in front of a hospital.

867
00:49:53,500 --> 00:49:56,375
I'm staying low just in case.
You guys should do the same.

868
00:49:57,083 --> 00:50:00,500
Don't even know why we snatched him.
What did he do anyway, huh?

869
00:50:00,583 --> 00:50:01,958
No business of mine, really.

870
00:50:02,041 --> 00:50:06,416
The story is the guy was getting cocky
and causing trouble,

871
00:50:06,500 --> 00:50:08,541
so I was asked to teach him a lesson.

872
00:50:08,625 --> 00:50:10,500
[breathing heavily]

873
00:50:11,041 --> 00:50:12,166
[Inukai] What's this?

874
00:50:16,791 --> 00:50:18,333
He heard what we were saying.

875
00:50:31,416 --> 00:50:34,250
This kid's face is even more annoying
than his father's.

876
00:50:35,541 --> 00:50:37,541
[music increases in tempo]

877
00:50:42,916 --> 00:50:44,250
Change of plans.

878
00:50:48,625 --> 00:50:50,666
It turns out I've gotta go.

879
00:50:50,750 --> 00:50:53,250
I'm on my way to visit Mr. Morita, anyway.

880
00:50:55,458 --> 00:50:57,166
I'm grateful to you, Mr. Kujo.

881
00:50:58,500 --> 00:51:02,291
Other attorneys just worry about covering
their asses, so they play it safe.

882
00:51:03,541 --> 00:51:04,750
You're not like that.

883
00:51:05,916 --> 00:51:09,583
When it comes to fighting
for your clients, you give it all you got.

884
00:51:20,791 --> 00:51:23,375
[Kujo] Has everything been okay
since my last visit?

885
00:51:25,583 --> 00:51:26,416
Huh?

886
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:28,666
[Kujo] Are you still clamming up?

887
00:51:30,666 --> 00:51:31,583
Uh-huh.

888
00:51:36,000 --> 00:51:37,083
Um…

889
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:41,833
Well?

890
00:51:44,000 --> 00:51:47,625
I wanna know… [hesitates]
…can I switch lawyers?

891
00:51:47,708 --> 00:51:50,291
- [dramatic sting]
- [music calms]

892
00:51:50,375 --> 00:51:53,000
'Cause… my dad,

893
00:51:53,083 --> 00:51:55,958
he's got this attorney
he wants me to use, right?

894
00:51:59,875 --> 00:52:01,875
[music increases in tempo]

895
00:52:19,625 --> 00:52:20,833
[knocks on door]

896
00:52:21,750 --> 00:52:22,916
[music fades]

897
00:52:28,541 --> 00:52:31,000
Just been fired? That's gotta suck.

898
00:52:36,125 --> 00:52:39,291
Oh, yeah. You missed your pal.
Mr. Karasuma just left.

899
00:52:41,333 --> 00:52:42,416
Karasuma was here?

900
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:45,583
Yeah,
we had a whole lot of questions for him.

901
00:52:47,666 --> 00:52:48,958
About Mr. Morita.

902
00:53:01,375 --> 00:53:02,708
Mr. Karasuma.

903
00:53:04,416 --> 00:53:05,333
Oh, hello.

904
00:53:07,833 --> 00:53:08,750
Are you okay?

905
00:53:14,250 --> 00:53:17,541
Listen, Mr. Kujo,
can I ask you for a favor?

906
00:53:19,625 --> 00:53:20,458
Of course.

907
00:53:22,333 --> 00:53:24,666
I'd like to have one
of those coffees you make.

908
00:53:29,250 --> 00:53:30,333
Thanks.

909
00:53:41,958 --> 00:53:42,833
[sighs]

910
00:53:45,750 --> 00:53:46,875
Back at the station,

911
00:53:46,958 --> 00:53:49,750
Detective Arashiyama was asking you
about Morita's case, wasn't he?

912
00:53:50,666 --> 00:53:51,625
Yes.

913
00:53:53,000 --> 00:53:54,333
[Kujo] Are you sure you're okay?

914
00:53:56,041 --> 00:53:58,791
Don't worry about it.
I made sure not to say anything.

915
00:53:59,541 --> 00:54:00,458
No.

916
00:54:01,208 --> 00:54:03,625
It's you I'm worried about, Mr. Karasuma.

917
00:54:03,708 --> 00:54:06,666
Don't worry about me.
You should be worrying about yourself.

918
00:54:08,458 --> 00:54:11,375
Arashiyama is no longer being selective
about his methods.

919
00:54:11,875 --> 00:54:12,875
He's going after everyone

920
00:54:12,958 --> 00:54:15,125
who might get him closer to the truth
about his daughter.

921
00:54:15,208 --> 00:54:17,125
Mibu and Kyogoku are
at the top of the list.

922
00:54:18,125 --> 00:54:19,958
And you're also one of his targets,
Mr. Kujo.

923
00:54:20,875 --> 00:54:22,083
Yeah, I'm aware of that.

924
00:54:27,583 --> 00:54:29,375
He's got some real solid evidence.

925
00:54:32,416 --> 00:54:34,708
Morita informed me
he's no longer my client.

926
00:54:39,583 --> 00:54:41,833
He'll probably cut a deal
and make a statement.

927
00:54:42,375 --> 00:54:43,625
What are you going to do?

928
00:54:45,791 --> 00:54:48,875
I'll see it through.
I'll do whatever I have to do.

929
00:54:50,708 --> 00:54:53,291
Is protecting gangsters and lowlifes
like Mibu and Kyogoku

930
00:54:53,375 --> 00:54:55,000
something you have to do?

931
00:54:57,458 --> 00:54:59,750
As a lawyer,
I'm obliged to protect my client.

932
00:55:01,458 --> 00:55:03,416
Even if you're walking into an ambush?

933
00:55:04,166 --> 00:55:07,500
They'll sell you out to protect themselves
like Morita's doing now.

934
00:55:09,375 --> 00:55:11,458
It's dangerous to get too close
to your clients.

935
00:55:11,541 --> 00:55:13,083
You have to look out for yourself first.

936
00:55:13,166 --> 00:55:14,250
Mr. Karasuma.

937
00:55:16,083 --> 00:55:19,625
In this city it might seem as if
we can do whatever we want,

938
00:55:19,708 --> 00:55:23,083
<i>but we're actually constrained by</i>
<i>endless rules and regulations.</i>

939
00:55:24,500 --> 00:55:28,125
<i>An invisible network of laws</i>
<i>controls our daily lives.</i>

940
00:55:30,166 --> 00:55:32,208
I believe the law has one great virtue.

941
00:55:32,958 --> 00:55:35,250
We're all equal
because it treats us impartially.

942
00:55:35,833 --> 00:55:38,250
I'm not looking for a textbook answer.

943
00:55:38,333 --> 00:55:39,833
I wanna know what motivates you.

944
00:55:39,916 --> 00:55:41,375
[melancholy music playing]

945
00:55:41,458 --> 00:55:42,666
Motivates me?

946
00:55:42,750 --> 00:55:44,500
After my dad was murdered,

947
00:55:45,041 --> 00:55:48,750
my mother was mocked constantly,
so she just shut down all of her feelings.

948
00:55:50,125 --> 00:55:51,416
You're just like her.

949
00:55:52,291 --> 00:55:55,125
There's a look in your eyes like
my mother had when she was in pain.

950
00:55:56,666 --> 00:55:58,458
Keep this up and you're risking disgrace.

951
00:55:58,541 --> 00:56:00,583
The world will hate you,
and you'll lose everything.

952
00:56:00,666 --> 00:56:02,791
How will you be able to handle
all that pressure?

953
00:56:05,958 --> 00:56:06,833
[sighs]

954
00:56:06,916 --> 00:56:08,375
To be honest with you…

955
00:56:13,416 --> 00:56:14,375
I'm scared.

956
00:56:15,958 --> 00:56:16,916
Terrified.

957
00:56:19,875 --> 00:56:22,291
I may be a lawyer,
but I'm also a human being.

958
00:56:24,166 --> 00:56:25,916
My name may spell it backwards…

959
00:56:28,458 --> 00:56:30,291
but I'm just as human as you are.

960
00:56:33,000 --> 00:56:34,041
[sighs]

961
00:56:34,125 --> 00:56:35,500
[music increases in tempo]

962
00:56:41,625 --> 00:56:44,208
The first time I took on a case
defending a gangster

963
00:56:44,291 --> 00:56:46,125
when I was starting out as a lawyer,

964
00:56:47,166 --> 00:56:48,375
I felt conflicted.

965
00:56:50,875 --> 00:56:53,708
I wondered if what I was doing
was really the right thing.

966
00:56:57,791 --> 00:57:00,041
But if I had refused
to be the guy's attorney,

967
00:57:00,750 --> 00:57:03,500
another lawyer would still
have had to do the job.

968
00:57:05,541 --> 00:57:09,000
The same goes for those who are mistreated
because they have no money.

969
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:12,541
I mean, your average lawyer,

970
00:57:13,125 --> 00:57:16,125
they won't go near a case
that involves the weak and the poor.

971
00:57:19,166 --> 00:57:21,000
I learned that from experience.

972
00:57:23,083 --> 00:57:25,333
The law may protect people's basic rights,

973
00:57:26,083 --> 00:57:28,500
but it can't protect people's lives.

974
00:57:29,416 --> 00:57:32,500
If I really wanted to help
the most defenseless in society,

975
00:57:33,541 --> 00:57:36,541
I would have to be willing
to get my hands dirty and enter the jungle

976
00:57:36,625 --> 00:57:40,500
where the strong prey on the weak
and face the worst of humanity.

977
00:57:44,791 --> 00:57:48,875
When a lawyer manages to save one,
they bring sorrow to another.

978
00:57:51,833 --> 00:57:53,708
That's what it means to be a lawyer.

979
00:57:54,750 --> 00:57:56,833
So I decided to carry
the weight of that sin.

980
00:57:58,083 --> 00:58:01,125
But if you're disbarred and you lose
your license, you won't be a lawyer.

981
00:58:01,625 --> 00:58:03,208
All your noble aims are meaningless

982
00:58:03,291 --> 00:58:05,333
if you can't help people
defend their rights.

983
00:58:06,291 --> 00:58:08,041
You can't help anyone if you're dead.

984
00:58:11,000 --> 00:58:13,291
I don't want you to die, Mr. Kujo.

985
00:58:13,375 --> 00:58:15,375
[music fades]

986
00:58:17,166 --> 00:58:18,875
I want you to keep being a lawyer.

987
00:58:23,958 --> 00:58:25,250
Mr. Karasuma.

988
00:58:28,500 --> 00:58:29,791
Thank you so much.

989
00:58:33,291 --> 00:58:36,708
All this reminds me of what your mother
was saying about your father.

990
00:58:37,375 --> 00:58:39,791
The way a person chooses to live

991
00:58:40,833 --> 00:58:43,166
is revealed in the moment of their death.

992
00:58:45,208 --> 00:58:46,916
The way a person dies

993
00:58:48,500 --> 00:58:50,375
is also the way they lived.

994
00:58:52,458 --> 00:58:55,166
Even if I'm disbarred,
even if I die as a lawyer,

995
00:58:56,125 --> 00:58:58,625
this is the way
I have chosen to live my life.

996
00:59:00,500 --> 00:59:03,041
And I'm doing something
that only I can do.

997
00:59:04,833 --> 00:59:08,041
So… I'm ready…

998
00:59:10,500 --> 00:59:12,208
for whatever awaits me.

999
00:59:12,291 --> 00:59:14,291
[dramatic music playing]

1000
00:59:23,500 --> 00:59:25,583
[Inukai] Let's chop him up
and stick him in this box.

1001
00:59:29,125 --> 00:59:30,291
Wait a minute!

1002
00:59:31,083 --> 00:59:33,083
My old man is a big deal
in the Fushimi-gumi!

1003
00:59:33,166 --> 00:59:34,833
His name is Kiyoshi Kyogoku!

1004
00:59:35,333 --> 00:59:37,250
If you do this, there's no going back!

1005
00:59:37,333 --> 00:59:38,500
Is that so?

1006
00:59:40,291 --> 00:59:42,375
Then that's all the more reason
to shut you up.

1007
00:59:42,458 --> 00:59:43,791
[saw whirring]

1008
00:59:46,500 --> 00:59:50,291
[henchman 1] Boss, no one around here
saw Takeshi yesterday. [groans]

1009
00:59:50,375 --> 00:59:52,000
- Just keep looking!
- [henchman 2 grunts]

1010
00:59:52,500 --> 00:59:53,833
I have a bad feeling.

1011
00:59:54,875 --> 00:59:56,458
My gut's never been wrong.

1012
00:59:56,541 --> 00:59:57,916
No, please!

1013
00:59:58,000 --> 00:59:59,000
[saw whirring]

1014
00:59:59,083 --> 01:00:00,583
Let me go!

1015
01:00:02,000 --> 01:00:02,833
Mibu!

1016
01:00:04,291 --> 01:00:07,291
Someone named Yamamoto
knows where Inukai's hideout is.

1017
01:00:07,916 --> 01:00:09,625
We gotta get there before Kyogoku. Get in.

1018
01:00:09,708 --> 01:00:10,583
Yes, sir.

1019
01:00:15,458 --> 01:00:17,166
Get any information you can.

1020
01:00:17,250 --> 01:00:18,666
Find out where Takeshi went.

1021
01:00:19,166 --> 01:00:21,000
Find him no matter what!

1022
01:00:22,250 --> 01:00:23,750
[screams]

1023
01:00:23,833 --> 01:00:25,708
[Takeshi] Please just stop!

1024
01:00:26,500 --> 01:00:28,250
No!

1025
01:00:28,333 --> 01:00:30,333
- [screams]
- [Inukai chuckles]

1026
01:00:31,291 --> 01:00:32,708
[music quiets]

1027
01:00:36,833 --> 01:00:38,500
[Karasuma] This is my last question.

1028
01:00:39,250 --> 01:00:40,208
[Kujo] Okay.

1029
01:00:41,416 --> 01:00:42,666
Mr. Kujo, do you…

1030
01:00:46,333 --> 01:00:47,958
do you need me or not?

1031
01:00:54,791 --> 01:00:55,750
No.

1032
01:00:58,333 --> 01:00:59,416
I don't need you.

1033
01:00:59,916 --> 01:01:01,916
[music crescendoes]

1034
01:01:03,708 --> 01:01:04,666
Understood.

1035
01:01:40,083 --> 01:01:41,458
Attorney Taiza Kujo…

1036
01:01:43,833 --> 01:01:45,208
my time with you was short…

1037
01:01:47,583 --> 01:01:49,041
but thank you for everything.

1038
01:01:51,625 --> 01:01:52,583
Thank you very much.

1039
01:02:00,541 --> 01:02:01,583
Excuse me.

1040
01:02:28,500 --> 01:02:30,708
[closing theme song playing]

1041
01:07:17,000 --> 01:07:18,416
[music fades]
